  <front>
   <head>[Sketch of his Own Character]</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="sestet">
     <l n="1" met="-+|--+|--+|--+|-" line_length="12">Too poor for a bribe and too proud to importune,</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|--+|--+|--+|-" line_length="12">He had not the method of making a fortune:</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="11">Could love and could hate, so was thought somewhat odd;</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="11">No very great wit, he believed in a God.</l>
     <l n="5" met="-+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="11">A post or a pension he did not desire,</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="11">But left church and state to Charles Townshend and Squire.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
